hat have allowed for the estimation of sea ice formation rates, a parameter that is otherwise difficult to obtain, while also providing a unique description of the wintertime ocean circulation over the central Weddell Sea continental shelf. Finally, we present the first data collected by a newly-developed fluorescence sensor that has been embedded in the regular CTD-SRDL and deployed on elephant seals at Kerguelen. The fluorometer data obtained have offered the first synoptic view of the 3 dimensional distribution of temperature, salinity and fluorescence over a vast sector of the Southern Indian Ocean, allowing us to describe both vertical and horizontal variations in chlorophyll. This paper will make a core contribution to the Plenary Sessions 2C, 3A and 4A, and will be relevant to 2A and 2B},
author = {Charrassin, J B and Roquet, F and Park, Y H and Bailleul, F and Guinet, C and Meredith, Michael M and Nicholls, Keith and Thorpe, Sally and McDonald, B and Costa, D P and Tremblay, I and Goebel, M and Muelbert, M and Bester, M N and Pl{\"{o}}tz, J and Bornemann, H and Timmermann, R and Hindell, M and Meijers, A and Coleman, R C and Field, I C and McMahon, C M and Rintoul, S R and Sokolov, S and Boehme, Lars and Lovell, P and Fedak, M A and Biuw, Martin and N{\o}st, O A and Lydersen, C and Kovacs, K M},
