ch, with higher speeds reached in the weighted condition and at steeper pitch. A simple physical model allowed us to estimate the body density of the seal from the speed and pitch (1,027-1,046 kg m(-3), roughly corresponding to 32-41% lipid content, for the weighted condition; 1,014-1,022 kg m(-3), 43-47% lipid content, for the unweighted condition).},
author = {Watanabe, Yuuki and Baranov, Eugene a and Sato, Katsufumi and Naito, Yasuhiko and Miyazaki, Nobuyuki},
doi = {10.1242/jeb.02402},
file = {:C\:/Users/a5406/AppData/Local/Mendeley Ltd./Mendeley Desktop/Downloaded/Watanabe et al. - 2006 - Body density affects stroke patterns in Baikal seals.pdf:pdf},
issn = {0022-0949},
journal = {J. Exp. Biol.},
keywords = {Acceleration,Animals,Biomechanical Phenomena,Body Composition,Body Composition: physiology,Diving,Diving: physiology,Female,Forelimb,Forelimb: physiology,Fresh Water,Male,Models, Theoretical,Phoca,Phoca: physiology,Russia,Swimming,Swimming: physiology},
